"{'title': 'Church: a language for generative models', 'authors': [{'forename': 'Noah', 'surname': 'Goodman', 'email': None, 'affiliation_name': 'MIT BCS/CSAIL Cambridge', 'affiliation_country': None}, {'forename': 'Vikash', 'surname': 'Mansinghka', 'email': None, 'affiliation_name': 'MIT BCS/CSAIL Cambridge', 'affiliation_country': None}, {'forename': 'Daniel', 'surname': 'Roy', 'email': None, 'affiliation_name': 'MIT BCS/CSAIL Cambridge', 'affiliation_country': None}, {'forename': 'Keith', 'surname': 'Bonawitz', 'email': None, 'affiliation_name': 'MIT BCS/CSAIL Cambridge', 'affiliation_country': None}, {'forename': 'Joshua', 'surname': 'Tenenbaum', 'email': None, 'affiliation_name': 'MIT BCS/CSAIL Cambridge', 'affiliation_country': None}], 'abstract': 'Formal languages for probabilistic modeling enable re-use, modularity, and descriptive clarity, and can foster generic inference techniques. We introduce Church, a universal language for describing stochastic generative processes. Church is based on the Lisp model of lambda calculus, containing a pure Lisp as its deterministic subset. The semantics of Church is defined in terms of evaluation histories and conditional distributions on such histories. Church also includes a novel language construct, the stochastic memoizer, which enables simple description of many complex non-parametric models. We illustrate language features through several examples, including: a generalized Bayes net in which parameters cluster over trials, infinite PCFGs, planning by inference, and various non-parametric clustering models. Finally, we show how to implement query on any Church program, exactly and approximately, using Monte Carlo techniques.', 'acknowledgements': '<ontology_classes.Aknowledgement object at 0x000002937423F610>', 'references': [{'cites': <ontology_classes.Paper object at 0x00000293742911D0>, 'date': '1996'}, {'cites': <ontology_classes.Paper object at 0x0000029374291750>, 'date': '2002'}, {'cites': <ontology_classes.P